The fires, he said, were all situated in rural areas in the mountains
where it would be difficult to fight them.

&quot;(Arson) is the impression we got from the people we talked to,&quot; Ron
said. &quot;Whomever was setting these fires knew the larger cities would
have the resources to fight them and that it would take days to
extinguish a fire in a remote area. There must have been a method to
their madness.&quot;

Many people, Zgud said, laid blame on socialist leader George
Papandreou. But he wasn't the only one to escape criticism. Polls
indicated growing anger with the conservative government for
mishandling the firefighting efforts.

Such accusations forced Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis to promise
the equivalent of C$18,800 in aid per family.

&quot;There were 4,000 homes and buildings destroyed and 76 lives lost
during the week of wildfires,&quot; Zgud said. &quot;It was estimated that 2.2
billion (Euros) worth of damage was caused and the livelihood of
hundreds of people lost.&quot;

Zgud said leading up to his departure for Greece, second thoughts had
crossed his mind about actually going. However, he said he has no
regrets and he and his wife plan to return to Greece in the years to
come to see how well the country has recovered.

